                type="document" xml:id="d761">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On September 21, 1950, the <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> adopted a policy
                    decision restoring to Japanese courts (at the discretion of <gloss
                        target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss>) the exercise of criminal jurisdiction over
                    United Nations nationals with exception of occupation forces and related
                    categories. Text of the policy decision and of the draft directive which
                    resulted from it are attached to a letter of September 21 from Nelson T.
                    Johnson, Secretary-General of the <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss>, to Mr.
                    Webb, Acting Secretary. (None printed; 690.00–<gloss target="#t_FEC1"
                        >FEC</gloss>/9–2150)</p>
                <p>The United States had initiated this action. In telegram 66 to Canberra,
                    September 15, the Department had stated in part: “In view Korean crisis US
                    considers approval of this paper as matter urgency in order to reduce burden on
                    occupation forces in Japan.” (690.00–<gloss target="#t_FEC1"
                    >FEC</gloss>/9–1550)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
